{"title": "New York Today: The New Travel Ban", "url": "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/07/nyregion/new-york-today-what-you-need-to-know-about-the-travel-ban.html?mcubz=0", "text": "What should New Yorkers with relatives traveling to the United States from the banned six countries know?\n\nIf a relative already has a visa, in theory, that person should be fine, said Camille Mackler, the director of legal initiatives at the New York Immigration Coalition. But that individual may be stopped and questioned, so be prepared. Stay in contact with the relative during his or her travel.\n\n\u201cIf they do not yet have an approved visa, then it looks like they are out of luck,\u201d she said, at least for the first 90 days after the new ban is in place.\n\nHere\u2019s what else is happening:\n\nWeather\n\nWhen \u201cAnnie\u201d sang about a day that\u2019s gray (and lonely), perhaps she was talking about this one.\n\nYou\u2019re waking up to overcast, sleepy skies and can expect on-and-off light rain \u2014 and a high of 54 \u2014 for most of today.\n\nMeh.\n\nThe sun will come out \u2014 on Thursday.\n\nIn the News\n\n\u2022 Residents of Champlain, N.Y., watch as migrants use a quiet, country road to reach Canada, where they can seek asylum. [New York Times]\n\nPhoto\n\n\u2022 After spying on Muslims, the Police Department has agreed to greater oversight of its intelligence-gathering programs. [New York Times]\n\nAdvertisement Continue reading the main story\n\n\u2022 After a life of lawbreaking, Kwauhuru Govan has been charged with killing two Brooklyn teenagers more than a decade ago. [New York Times]\n\n\u2022 The downside of ride-hailing apps: They\u2019re an existential threat to taxis and are raising concerns of worsening congestion. [New York Times]\n\nPhoto\n\n\u2022 Andrew Giuliani, the son of Rudolph W. Giuliani, the former mayor, has joined the Trump administration. [Politico]\n\n\u2022 There were four times more heroin overdoses in the city last year than there were murders, the police said. [DNAinfo]\n\n\u2022 A visitor at the Metropolitan Museum of Art smashed a bottle on the head of a security guard. [Gothamist]\n\n\u2022 Today\u2019s Metropolitan Diary: \u201cLooking for Connie Anderson\u201d\n\n\u2022 Scoreboard: Knicks mangle Magic, 113-105. Nets trap Grizzlies, 122-109. Rangers slight Lightning, 1-0 (in overtime).\n\nNewsletter Sign Up Continue reading the main story Please verify you're not a robot by clicking the box. Invalid email address. Please re-enter. You must select a newsletter to subscribe to. Sign Up You agree to receive occasional updates and special offers for The New York Times's products and services. Thank you for subscribing. An error has occurred. Please try again later. View all New York Times newsletters.\n\n\u2022 For a global look at what\u2019s happening, see Your Tuesday Briefing.\n\nComing Up Today\n\n\u2022 Mayor Bill de Blasio will meet with Jewish community leaders at the JCC of Staten Island. 11:15 a.m.\n\n\u2022 Get a free short-stack at IHOP in honor of National Pancake Day. [Various locations]\n\n\u2022 The artist Sol Aramendi leads a photography workshop in Spanish at the Noguchi Museum in Astoria, Queens. 10 a.m. [Free]\n\n\u2022 Before it closes on Sunday, see the exhibition \u201cA Revolutionary Impulse: The Rise of the Russian Avant-Garde\u201d at the Museum of Modern Art. 10:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. [$25]\n\nAdvertisement Continue reading the main story\n\n\u2022 A screening of the Hungarian film \u201cKills on Wheels,\u201d part of the ReelAbilities Film Festival, at the St. George Library Center on Staten Island. 6 p.m. [Free]\n\n\u2022 Eighty one-minute plays by 50 playwrights will be performed at the One Minute Play Festival at the New Ohio Theater in Greenwich Village. 8 p.m. [$20]\n\n\u2022 Devils at Blue Jackets, 7 p.m. (MSG+). Nets at Hawks, 7:30 p.m. (YES). Rangers at Panthers, 7:30 p.m. (MSG). Knicks at Bucks, 8 p.m. (MSG). Islanders at Oilers, 9 p.m. (MS+2).\n\n\u2022 For more events, see The New York Times\u2019s Arts & Entertainment guide.\n\nCommute\n\n\u2022 Subway and PATH\n\n\u2022 Railroads: L.I.R.R., Metro-North, N.J. Transit, Amtrak\n\n\u2022 Roads: Check traffic map or radio report on the 1s or the 8s.\n\n\u2022 Alternate-side parking: in effect until March 12.\n\n\u2022 Ferries: Staten Island Ferry, New York Waterway, East River Ferry\n\n\u2022 Airports: La Guardia, J.F.K., Newark\n\nAnd Finally...\n\nPhoto\n\nThe world is still waiting for a giraffe upstate to give birth.\n\nThe Animal Adventure Park in Harpursville, N.Y., recently posted a live stream of April, a 15-year-old pregnant giraffe. The video gets an impressive five million or so views a day.\n\n(An update for April fans: An imprint of a face and neck of a young giraffe appeared in April\u2019s bedding and some are calling it an omen of impending birth.)\n\nAdvertisement Continue reading the main story\n\nOf course, animals aren\u2019t the only stars of live streams in New York: You are, too.\n\nViewers around the world can watch the sun rise over the Brooklyn Bridge or relax while staring at the surf at Rockaway Beach or Coney Island.\n\nAnd even those in isolated hamlets can experience the chaos of rush-hour in Times Square or view the congestion on our streets with one of the hundreds of cameras operated by the Department of Transportation.\n\nSo smile this morning on your commute; you could be on camera.\n\nNew York Today is a weekday roundup that stays live from 6 a.m. till late morning. You can receive it via email.\n\nFor updates throughout the day, like us on Facebook.\n\nWhat would you like to see here to start your day? Post a comment, email us at nytoday@nytimes.com, or reach us via Twitter using #NYToday.\n\nFollow the New York Today columnists, Alexandra Levine and Jonathan Wolfe, on Twitter.\n\nYou can find the latest New York Today at nytoday.com.", "publish_date": "2017-03-07", "authors": "Liz Robbins and Jonathan  Wolfe", "type": "article"}